#ELLEBeauty: Frizz driving you cray-cray? We’re not even going to begin to draw parallels with a certain Ms. Geller who feels the exact same way! Owing to the excessive humidity in the air during the monsoon, frizzy hair is very common this time of the year, and unless you think you’re starring in your own sitcom, this is really not a great look!

Introducing moisture into the hair shaft and locking that in can greatly reduce the pain that is frizz. Let’s take a look at some products that can help achieve this. Head to the 🔗 in bio.
.

Video via: @giphy 
.

#ELLEFashion: Transcending 4 generations—@ekayabanaras 120 years of legacy is built over the commitment of its founding family and the community of 10,000+ weavers. But it is over the last 10 years that Ekaya cemented its position as one of India’s premium luxury handloom textile labels, by bridging the gap between the weavers and the designers. 

As the brand steps into its second decade, Ekaya has launched the ‘Project Second Chance’. With this initiative, the label is inviting its patrons to find new ways to not just rewear their Ekaya, but also share their Ekaya wardrobe. Besides this, the brand also plans on teaching its consumers how to preserve, upcycle, re-style and revive their textiles in more ways than one. Tap the 🔗 in bio to learn more about this mindful initiative from co-founder @palakshah and how it will contribute towards circular fashion. 
.
Words by: @ruman02
Video via: @ekayabanaras 
.
#Ekaya #Textiles #IndianTextiles #IndianWeaves #Heritage #BenarasiWeaves #Fashion #Style

#ELLECulture: The internet was quick to label Sushmita Sen (@sushmitasen47) as a gold digger last week when Lalit Modi made a very public announcement about their relationship. From choosing not to get married and adopting two girls to dating a man fifteen years younger than her— it’s not the first time that Sushmita’s life decisions have been questioned and ridiculed. She won Miss Universe at the tender age of 18, adopted Renee at 24, battled Addison’s disease in 2014, made her acting comeback with the fierce Aarya in 2020, won a National Award for Social Welfare And Women Empowerment, and yet, all we focus on and reduce her to is her relationship status. Head to the 🔗 in bio to read about why policing her personal choices is problematic. 
.
Words: @glittterbugg 
Video via: Tenor
.
#SushmitaSen #LalitModi #Relationship #MissUniverse

#ELLECulture: TV watching might be a habit that’s finding fewer patrons, but all of us have been glued to the idiot box at some time, deeply interested in whatever it is showing at that point. It certainly has my attention when it’s funny. And in a lot of shows that haven’t aged well; I hear several comments attacking certain communities in ways that blatantly disrespect its members and each time I do, I die a little on the inside. If it wasn’t for the recent change in the television industry that expects new-age shows to actually build witty tropes and realistically funny character quirks, most of us would have to stop in our tracks thanks to the fat-shaming, casual racism, and obnoxious sexism. Fortunately, we have some shows to prove there is a lot of room to be hilarious whilst not being offensive. Head to the 🔗 in bio. 
.
Words: @deeya.sonalkar 
Video via: @giphy 
.
#TVShows #Sitcoms #FunnySitcoms #WhatToWatch

#ELLEDigitalCoverStars: Four towering figures in the realm of cinema meet at a cover shoot. How, you ask? Well, a cherished cinematic banner is being enkindled after 18 years– Bhushan Kumar and Anurag Basu’s ‘Metro…In Dino.’ One of them is championing pragmatism, and another seasoned player expresses gratitude for a life well-lived. One of them shares she devised a language made of symbols at the mere age of nine, leaving the writer deliciously stunned, and the fourth powerhouse is engaging in a mental slacklining of sorts–one that involves unlearning and surrender. This convergence of compelling women is bringing the good ole glory back to the big screen–and you’ve been summoned to meet them up close. Here’s a peek into the minds of Sara Ali Khan (@saraalikhan95), Neena Gupta (@neena_gupta), Konkona Sensharma (@konkona) and Fatima Sana Shaikh (@fatimasanashaikh) all uncontrived and warm. Read the full interview at the 🔗 in bio. 
.

#ELLECoverStar: It’s a hot, chaotic day in Mumbai. The traffic, the grind, and the sultriness are dialled up. Navya Naveli Nanda (@navyananda) is not fazed. She looks absolutely cool on a Monday that is anything but. You kind of expect a certain je ne sais quoi from a young woman who’s got the best of everything going for her. But from the time Nanda arrives to her being lensed over a few hours, she surprises you; she wraps none of that stardom around her as an identity. Instead, you meet someone who exudes a quiet purpose. She isn’t willing to just sit by and watch. Instead, she’s been facilitating change for women and empowering them to find financial independence. Head to the 🔗 in the bio to read the full conversation with our cover star.________________________________
On @navyananda: Beige dress by @amg_brand. Hat by @vvrouleaux. Santos-Dumont watch, Baignoire watch, Classic Love bracelet in rose gold and Love Torque necklace in rose gold, all by @cartier.

latestPosts.caption:
#ELLECulture: A new breed of musicians is taking flight–ones unafraid to break the mould and fuse genres. Signalling a defiant refusal to adhere to tradition, India’s music scene is now welcomingly hellbent on challenging the status quo while giving us bop after bop to add to our playlists. However, for every note they play, there’s a risk: the risk of alienating family, the risk of being misunderstood and the risk of failure in a system that favours conformity. And that’s what they want to talk about. So, this World Music Day, let’s hear it from them, at the 🔗 in bio.
.
Words by @ipsitakaul
.
#WorldMusicDay #IndianArtists #NewMusic #IndianMusic #MusicRadar

#ELLEWellness: Ending your week stressed out with too many things at hand—time-demanding tasks, that nagging back ache and the all-pervading monsoon gloom? This time, skip that trip to the cinema or coffee shop, to unwind. Instead, head into a ‘Mewga’ class where people are performing yoga moves with furry felines. It’s a trend that has been catching on in busy cities—giving folks some downtime, more than a few cuddly moments and making for a cool wellness grab. Ahead of International Yoga Day, we checked out Mumbai’s Cat Café where that paw-sitivity is making for a fun way to exercise. Read more about it at the 🔗 in bio.
